Since, we have already determined each expected return of the state of the economy, let us now compute the expected return of the portfolio. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{array}{l}
\text{Portfolio expected return}={\sum_\text{}}{\text{(Probability return $\times$ Expected return)}}\\
\hspace{110pt}={\text{(10\% $\times$ 34.60\%) + (60\% $\times$ 14\%)}}\\[5pt]
\hspace{120pt} + {\text{(25\% $\times$ -2.70\%)}} 
{\text{ + (5\% $\times$ -13.50\%)}}\\[5pt]
\hspace{110pt}={\text{3.46\% + 8.40\% - 0.68\% - 0.68\%}}\\[5pt]
\hspace{110pt}= {\textbf{10.50\%}}
\end{array}$$

**The portfolio expected return is 10.50%.**

Now, let us compute the standard deviation of the portfolio by determining the square root of the variance that we have computed in step 10. This is computed as follows: 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Standard deviation}&= {\sqrt { 0.0137791}}\\
&= {\textbf{11.74\%}}
\end{aligned}$$

**The standard deviation of the portfolio is 11.74%.**
